@flexiarg depositing/upstream-patch-signal
@title Upstream Patches as Consulting Signal
@references-extra ["depositing/scan-talk-frame (scan identifies patch targets)" "depositing/grant-to-pitch (patches demonstrate the same capability that grants propose)" "war-machine/cardinal-directions (patches are depositing in the open-source economy)"]

! conclusion: Treat merged upstream patches as consulting signal: a public change to a codebase the client already cares about says more than self-promotion ever can.

  + CONTEXT:
     A practitioner wants to signal expertise to potential clients or employers but dislikes self-promotion. Blog posts, talks, and social media feel performative.

  + IF:
     The practitioner uses open-source dependencies deeply enough to find bugs, missing features, or design improvements.

  + HOWEVER:
     Sending one patch to one project is invisible. Writing blog posts about capabilities feels hollow without evidence.

  + THEN:
     Systematically identify patch opportunities in the upstream dependency network. Prioritise patches to projects with commercial ecosystems (XTDB, Datahike, Logseq) or active communities (Reagent, Malli). Each merged patch is a permanent, verifiable signal that says "I understand your codebase well enough to improve it."

    + NOTE:
       The Drawbridge CIDER adapter is the prototype instance: a real gap (no existing adapter), deep expertise (daily use of Drawbridge in the stack), and high visibility (every CIDER user would benefit). Estimated effort: 2-3 days. Signal value: permanent.

  + BECAUSE:
     A merged PR is the strongest possible consulting signal. It is not self-promotion - it is demonstrated competence, publicly verifiable, attached to a real codebase the client cares about. The practitioner's dependency graph IS their professional network; patches are introductions.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Maintain a ranked patch target list drawn from the dependency graph and treat each merged upstream contribution as both depositing and lead-generation evidence.]
